results.lead_paragraph: BUTTON-EYED, about to burst into tears, the trembling, pigtailed refugee tugged at the sleeve of a conspicuously expiring, modestly plump Orson Welles. That was 31 years ago, when Natalie Wood, the 7-year-old daughter of a Russian set designer and ballet dancer, began her Hollywood career by stealing scenes from the unsuspecting Welles and a weepy Claudette Colbert in the immortally schmaltzy "Tomorrow Is Forever."

headline.main: SALYUT 6 STATION PUT INTO ORBIT BY SOVIET; Launching Could Be a Prelude to Manned Mission in Time for Sputnik 20th Anniversary

results.snippet: The Soviet Union orbited yesterday a new space station, Salyut 6, in what could be a prelude to a manned mission in time for the 20th anniversary of the birth of the space era, the flight of Sputnik 1 on Oct. 4, 1957.
